</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,694,1414,1441]" box="[189,694,1414,1441]" pageId="10" pageNumber="173">
ADULT (
<figureCitation box="[281,369,1414,1441]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[189,232,1892,1918]" captionTargetBox="[190,1398,423,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-42@2.[190,1398,420,1853]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1.AdultsofAntiochtha spp. (dorsal view).A. A. erromerasp.nov., holotype(NKU).B. A. hainanensis sp. nov., paratype (NKU). C. A. jianfengensis Zhu &amp; Li, 2009, from Hainan, China. D. A. jianfengensis, holotype of A. rotunda syn. nov. from Guizhou, China. E. A. miniscula sp. nov., holotype. F. A. semialis Park, 2002. Scale bars = 2.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6784084" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6784084/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="173">Fig. 1F</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 14.0‒15.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[188,1399,1481,1725]" pageId="10" pageNumber="173">
FEMALE GENITALIA (
<figureCitation box="[411,506,1481,1507]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="8.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[243,1262,268,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-18@8.[203,1384,261,1877]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Fig. 4. Female genitalia of Antiochtha spp. A. A. erromera sp. nov., paratype, slide No. YS20065. B. A. hainanensis sp. nov., paratype, slide No. YS20228. C. A. jianfengensis, slide No. YS20074. D. A. semialis Park, 2002, slide No. YS20275. Scale bars = 0.5 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6784090" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6784090/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="173">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
). Eighth abdominal sternite represented by two large lateral plates, grooved vertically along midline. Apophyses posteriores slightly shorter than twice length of apophyses anteriores. Antrum weakly sclerotized, cup-shaped, spiculose. Ductus bursae longer than corpus bursae, twisted once anteriorly, with several thumbtack-shaped spines medially; ductus seminalis narrower than ductus bursae, helical, arising from about posterior ¼ of ductus bursae. Corpus bursae elliptical; signum situated at posterior 2/5, ovoid, serrate along margins, with a rectangular, horizontal central groove.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
